   "judge_reasoning": "The reflection forces citations onto what is largely routine scientific content. [2.1] is stretched—the text frames controlling infection as a public health priority, not as an engagement with the ethics of helping; the reflection's added contrast with 'mere convenience' is its own embellishment. [3.2] treats the mere presence of references as value engagement rather than standard scientific practice. [5.1] on adverse-event monitoring is similarly generic—reporting safety outcomes is standard clinical methodology, not a salient engagement with non-maleficence. The one clearly engaged value—[3.3] for the explicit admission that safety analyses are 'completely lacking'—is missed entirely. Specificity is strong: the reflection quotes actual phrases ('completely lacking,' 'critical public health') and cites concrete details (adverse event rates, reference count). Voice is natural and grounded in this text, not formulaic.",
   "old_judge_decision": "reject",
   "agree": true
